PSY100H1-F-20225.courseDescription: A brief introductory survey of psychology as both a biological and social science. Topics will include physiological, learning, perceptual, motivational, cognitive, developmental, personality, abnormal, and social psychology.
PSY100H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online.  Learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule.  Opportunities for synchronous activity with instructors and classmates (e.g., virtual office hours) will be made available, but will not be required.  All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY100H1-S-20225.courseDescription: A brief introductory survey of psychology as both a biological and social science. Topics will include physiological, learning, perceptual, motivational, cognitive, developmental, personality, abnormal, and social psychology.

PSY201H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Fundamentals of descriptive and inferential statistics, including population and sampling distributions, simple association, probability, estimation, and hypothesis testing.
PSY201H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Course content will be accessible online for students to view asynchronously.  Opportunities for synchronous activity with instructors and classmates (e.g., virtual office hours, review sessions) will be made available and will be recorded and posted for asynchronous access when possible. The schedule for synchronous activities is currently TBA.  All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY201H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Fundamentals of descriptive and inferential statistics, including population and sampling distributions, simple association, probability, estimation, and hypothesis testing.

PSY202H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Fundamentals of statistical analysis of experimental and observational data including linear models, the analysis of variance, a priori contrasts, post-hoc tests, power analysis and effect size calculations.
PSY202H1-S-20225.webTimetableInstructions: Students must also register for the mandatory tutorial when they register for this course.

PSY210H1-F-20225.courseDescription: The developmental approach to the study of behaviour with reference to sensorimotor skills, cognition, socialization, personality, and emotional behaviour.

PSY220H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Contemporary areas of research in social psychology: social perception, attitudes, inter-personal relations, and group processes.
PSY220H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Course content will be delivered through a combination of pre-recorded Content Lectures and linked live-streamed zoom Companion Lectures during a set time each week. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY230H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Theory and research in personality structure and dynamics: the interaction of cultural and biological factors in the development and expression of individual differences.
PSY230H1-S-20225.webTimetableInstructions: This course will be an online, asynchronous course. Lecture videos will be recorded and uploaded to the course website at the beginning of each week. Students will have the opportunity to attend synchronous office hours each week to ask questions and get feedback. There will also be opportunities for synchronous activities with your classmates. These activities may be completed alone for those that cannot attend the synchronous sessions. The synchronous sessions are not mandatory and will not be recorded. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY240H1-F-20225.courseDescription: A critical survey of concepts, theories, and the state of research in the area of psychopathology and therapeutic methods.
PSY240H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: This is an online, asynchronous course. Lectures will be given as 2-3 hour online videos posted to YouTube and discussion/participation will be completed on Quercus. Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content. Students need the ability to read and edit PDFs or PowerPoint slides, and use Quercus for submission of discussion posts, the assignments and tests.

PSY260H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Concepts, theories, and applications of classical and contemporary learning theories, including classical and operant conditioning. Current theories of the physiological and anatomical basis of learning and memory, including synaptic plasticity, the role of the hippocampus, amygdala, frontal cortex and other brain regions. Theories will be related to a practical understanding and applications such as drug addiction, phobias and other disorders.
PSY260H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Lecture recordings will be available online for students to view asynchronously. Tutorial activities will be completed electronically asynchronously. Opportunities for synchronous activities (e.g. virtual office hours) will be available but optional or an asynchronous option will also be made available. Students will be able complete the course entirely asynchronously without it adversely impacting their mark.

PSY270H1-F-20225.courseDescription: An introduction to research and theory on the neural and cognitive architecture of attention, memory, language, thinking and reasoning.
PSY270H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: This course will be delivered as a combination of asynchronous and synchronous online activities.  Lectures will be given as a series of short videos totaling approximately 4 hours/week posted on Quercus before the designated class meeting time. Students are expected to attend live sessions via Zoom to participate in class activities and discussions during the scheduled class time (totaling approximately 2 hours/week). Students will have the opportunity to attend synchronous online office hours and Q&A sessions to ask questions. Students are expected to complete online homework via Top Hat each week.

PSY280H1-S-20225.courseDescription: An introduction to the physiological and psychological basis of perception across the different sensory modalities in humans and lower animals, with an emphasis on vision. Exploring visual perception such as shape and objects, scenes, colour, space, and motion as well as auditory perception of simple and complex sounds, and location. Further topics may include touch, including perception of temperature, pain and body posture, the chemical senses, and cross-modal influences of the senses on one another. In-class demonstrations may supplement the lectures.
PSY280H1-S-20225.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be pre-recorded and delivered online asynchronously. Online office hours via Zoom will be held on a weekly basis. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY290H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Provides students with a solid background in the biological basis of behaviour. Animal and human research topics will include functional neuroanatomy and neural signalling. Further topics may include sensory and motor control, motivational systems, hormones, and emotions, among other topics.
PSY290H1-S-20225.deliveryInstructions: All lectures and assessments will be available online. Recordings of lectures will be available for students to view asynchronously.

PSY299Y1-Y-20225.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at https://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/academics/research-opportunities/research-opportunities-program. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

PSY313H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Age changes in sensory and perceptual processes, motor skill, learning, memory, and personality. Theory, methodological problems, social, cultural, and environmental influences that shape behaviour and attitudes towards and among the elderly.

PSY319H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Provides an overview of developmental psychology methods. The class conducts an original research project, including design, data collection, data analysis, and a written report. Course capacity is limited to 15 students and priority is given to PSY Specialists and Research Specialists during the first enrolment period.

PSY320H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Intensive study of social attitude development, description, measurement, modification, and organization.

PSY321H1-F-20225.courseDescription: One of the hallmarks of human behaviour is its diversity. Some of the ways in which we differ are thought to be relatively idiosyncratic (e.g., specific aspects of personality); whereas others are fairly systematic. Cultural psychology is one area of research in human behaviour that examines systematic differences resulting from individuals’ cultural backgrounds. This course will introduce you to the consideration of cultural variation in the study of human thought and behaviour.
PSY321H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: This course will use a flipped classroom model of delivery.  Content will be pre-recorded, in-person sessions will involve active discussion and will be live-streamed, and all assessments will be online.  Therefore, this course could be completed by students unable to attend in-person.

PSY322H1-F-20225.courseDescription: An in-depth examination of theories and research in intergroup relations; focuses on stereotyping, prejudice, discrimination, and stigma.
PSY322H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered synchronously online via Zoom. All assessments will be completed online. Office hours will be offered virtually. All course deadlines will be given in Eastern time (i.e., Toronto time). Students will need a reliable internet connection, Zoom, Word, and access to free resources like Canva to complete this course.

PSY328H1-F-20225.courseDescription: This course deals with psychological issues in the law, with particular reference to criminal law. It focuses mainly on research that has been done on pretrial publicity, eyewitness testimony, rules of evidence, and other factors that might affect jury decisions.
PSY328H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: Course content will be delivered through a combination of pre-recorded Content Lectures and linked live-streamed zoom Companion Lectures during a set time each week. Students are expected to watch the Content Lecture before the live online Companion Lecture. All live-streamed content will be recorded to allow for asynchronous viewing. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY329H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Illustrates major methodologies within social psychology, such as attitude measurement, observation of small groups, and experiments. Course capacity is limited to 15 students and priority is given to PSY Specialists and Research Specialists during the first enrolment period.
PSY329H1-S-20225.deliveryInstructions: Course content will be delivered through a combination of pre-recorded (asynchronous) and live (synchronous) lectures. Students will be expected to watch asynchronous content prior to class meetings. Synchronous meetings will be delivered online (and recorded for later viewing or review). Students must have access to a computer that runs Windows, MacOS, or Linux, as a smartphone or tablet will not be sufficient for the data analysis component of the course. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY333H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Examines research evidence concerning the impact of psychological factors on physical health and illness.
PSY333H1-F-20225.prerequisite: PSY201H1/ECO220Y1/EEB225H1/GGR270H1/POL222H1/SOC202H1/STA220H1/STA238H1/STA248H1/STA288H1/PSY201H5/STA215H5/STA220H5/PSYB07H3/STAB22H3/STAB23H3/STAB57H3, and one of PSY230H1/PSY230H5/PSYB30H3 or PSY240H1/PSY240H5/PSYB32H3
PSY333H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: This is an online, asynchronous course. Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content. PSY336H1-S-20225.courseDescription: A review of the field of positive psychology, which is the study of happiness and fulfillment. Topics include personal growth, meaning, hedonic and eudaimonic approaches to well-being, gratitude, awe, flow states, mindfulness and meditation.
PSY336H1-S-20225.prerequisite: PSY201H1/ECO220Y1/EEB225H1/GGR270H1/POL222H1/SOC202H1/STA220H1/STA238H1/STA248H1/STA288H1/PSY201H5/STA215H5/STA220H5/PSYB07H3/STAB22H3/STAB23H3/STAB57H3, and one of PSY220H1/PSY220H5/PSYB10H3/SOC213H1 or PSY230H1/PSY230H5/PSYB30H3 or PSY240H1/PSY240H5/PSYB32H3

PSY343H1-F-20225.courseDescription: Examines various theories of how personality functioning may become impaired and corresponding psychotherapeutic interventions. Emphasis on empirical assessment of personality dysfunction and therapy effectiveness.
PSY343H1-F-20225.deliveryInstructions: This is an online, asynchronous course. PSY372H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Current theories and data on human memory: processes involved in encoding, storage, and retrieval.
PSY372H1-S-20225.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be pre-recorded, and delivered online asynchronously. All course assessments will be conducted online.

PSY396H1-F-20225.courseDescription: The functional relevance of neurotransmitters, with particular emphasis on their role in mediating behaviour.

PSY405H1-Y-20225.courseDescription: An intensive laboratory or applied research project under the supervision of a Department of Psychology faculty member. Project must be academically demanding and uniquely suitable for the individual student. Additional information and applications are available at the department and on its website. This course is open to all Psychology program students.
PSY405H1-Y-20225.prerequisite: PSY202H1/ECO220Y1/ECO227Y1/STA221H1/SOC252H1/SOC300H1, and appropriate background for the proposed work
PSY405H1-Y-20225.webTimetableInstructions: For PSY405H1Y and 406H1Y, 'E' indicator: Students must first obtain consent of a faculty member in the Department to supervise their project.  Information and application form is available on our website at https://psych.utoronto.ca/programs-and-courses/undergraduate-course-information.  The electronic application form, signed by both student and supervisor, should be submitted to the Undergraduate Administrator for approval via email (psy.undergrad@utoronto.ca).

PSY420H1-S-20225.courseDescription: Examination in depth of a limited topic within social psychology. Content in any given year depends on instructor. Course capacity is limited to 20 students and enrolment priority is given to PSY Specialists and Research Specialists.

LEC-0101.subtitle: Identity and Relationships in the Digital Age

PSY424H1-F-20225.courseDescription: This lecture course focuses on the social psychology of interpersonal relationships between individuals, especially romantic or close relationships and friendships. It surveys what social psychologists have learned about the development, maintenance, disruption or dissolution of personal relationships, as well as current social psychological theories of interpersonal relationships.

PSY424H1-S-20225.courseDescription: This lecture course focuses on the social psychology of interpersonal relationships between individuals, especially romantic or close relationships and friendships. It surveys what social psychologists have learned about the development, maintenance, disruption or dissolution of personal relationships, as well as current social psychological theories of interpersonal relationships.

PSY471H1-S-20225.courseDescription: An in-depth examination of current research and selected topics in cognitive psychology. Content in any given year depends on the instructor. Course capacity is limited to 20 students and enrolment priority is given to PSY Specialists and Research Specialists. There may be additional prerequisites based on the seminar topic given.

PSY493H1-S-20225.courseDescription: This is a capstone lecture course surveying research on how the mind arises from the brain. The first objective of the course is to understand how processes in human brains (ranging from the firing of a single neuron to the dynamics of billions) support cognitive abilities (such as recognizing a face, remembering a birthday from childhood, understanding the words in a spoken lecture, or planning a route home from class). The second objective of the course is to understand the methods of contemporary cognitive neuroscience research, to enable students to read primary literature and to understand ongoing debates.

PSY494H1-F-20225.courseDescription: This lecture course discusses the role of brain and body in the expression and experience of emotion in humans considered through the experimental, physiological, theoretical, and clinical literatures.
